I want to contribute as a forum for this discussion so better decisions are made and freedom grows rather than being stifled by concentration of power. I‚Äôm hear to listen and learn more.

One view is that regulations will better integrate Bitcoin in the financial system making on ramps simpler, speeding up adoption. 

The other view is government is inherently corrupt and incompetent and regulators will distort free markets and ultimately hold Bitcoin back.

There are competing views on whether regulations are good or bad, and what regulations are appropriate. 

Open debate is consistent with the core values of Bitcoin and I encourage it.

Attempts to regulate this space are likely in the next Congress. We need to vote for candidates who understand and support the core values of Bitcoin. Lots of great efforts are happening in this arena, but there is lots of work to be done to ensure Bitcoin is apolitical.

The 5% rule reminds me of one of my absolute favorite quotes by Ralph Waldo Emerson:

‚ÄúMake the most of yourself. For that is all there is of you.‚Äù

Thanks to my friend Cody for the inspo!

When you see a 5% relationship it‚Äôs truly inspiring. 

We all know people who fit into this category. And we know many more who unfortunately don‚Äôt. 

That doesn‚Äôt mean the 5% relationships don‚Äôt require work. In fact it‚Äôs the work and communication that builds a 5% foundation.

The 5% rule applies to relationships as well. I‚Äôd say only about 5% of relationships are truly amazing.

55% of marriages now end in divorce.

How many people stick it out because of kids? Money? Familiarity? Routine? Fear of the unknown? Insecurities? 

Then there‚Äôs the 5%.

There is a top 5% in every industry that lead innovation and dialogue: from doctors to teachers to poets to programmers. 

They get there because they have discipline, they have love for what they do, they have courage, and they work tirelessly to hone their talent and skills‚Ä¶

The 5% Rule‚Ä¶ a random, short üßµ

I was speaking with my friend about what he calls the 5% rule. I found it really motivating.

It applies to most things in life. 5% of people are the most successful, have the most money, are pioneers, are the most passionate, drive real change‚Ä¶

How'd I get my guests? That's one of the best things about the #Bitcoin & #cryptocurrency community. They are very open & receptive to people who want to learn about the space and the technology. People also love to talk about themselves and offer advice so it wasn't a hard sell.

I'm trying to save/invest as much as I can (hence the theme of the Coin Stories podcast) so I didn't want to spend money on things like a fancy cover photography shoot. I set up my iPhone 11 Pro on a tripod in the outdoor hallway of my apartment and shot my cover photos on timer. https://t.co/4WYInvkHXT

As for equipment -- I use the same equipment I have been using for my Career Stories podcast, which I'm proud to say is in its third season and is ranked internationally in the business category.  I use a Zoom recorder and 2 Audiotechnica Mics to record. @Adobe Audition to edit.

THREAD: I love all the questions I've been getting on my new podcast series, especially the ones about production. Many of you asked how I find time to do this on the side. I work before my day job starting at 5/6am, after my day job & on weekends! It's been a long few months.

Meanwhile, Huizar's trial date has officially been set for June 22, 2021. The @USAO_LosAngeles anticipates a grand jury will consider add'l charges against add'l defendants in a superseding indictment. Prosecutors will likely seek a unified trial date for all defendants.

Goldman is the fifth person to agree to plead guilty and cooperate with federal prosecutors. The others are former special aide to Huizar, George Esparza, political fundraiser Justin Kim, real estate consultant George Chiang, and former CM Mitch Englander. @SpecNews1SoCal

Goldman has deep ties to City Hall. He served as acting Chief of Staff to two former City Council members, Hal Bernson (District 12) and Mike Hernandez (District 1), before transitioning to lobbying and consulting, mainly on issues of land use and real estate development.

Side note - when filing the report below for @SpecNews1SoCal I interviewed multiple sources who didn't want to be identified but claimed there were developers in LA who felt pressured by CM Huizar to hire lobbyist Morrie Goldman for an $11k/month retainer. https://t.co/pbSSdUbyzt

Court filings also reveal that before September 2018, Company M contributed $50,000 to a PAC used to benefit Huizar‚Äôs political causes. In June 2018, Goldman secured a $25,000 contribution to the PAC for Richelle Huizar, plus a commitment for another $25,000 contribution.

In his plea agreement, Goldman admits that in Sep 2018 he agreed w/ Huizar and a Company M executive that the developer would contribute $50,000 to a PAC established to support Huizar's wife's political campaign. In return, Huizar would vote against a union appeal of the project.

Goldman's firm repped SF-based developer Carmel Partners on 520 Mateo, a proposed high-rise in the Arts District (Project M). Feds say thanks to Huizar, the development was approved with minimal affordable housing units, despite being in an area desperate for low-income housing.

Goldman (who is referred to as Lobbyist B in previous court filings) owns and operates the lobby firm Urban Solutions, LLC, which claims to specialize in negotiating and navigating City Hall approval for real estate projects, including hotels and high-rise apartment towers.

We're now in July. Fed up with the delays I decided to file a NEW request -- this one as limited as I could possibly make it. Again, my goal was to examine @lapublichealth's initial response/discussions surrounding #COVID19.  Here is the request I filed with @CountyofLA: https://t.co/E03WRxzr30

Spoke again to @CountyofLA and was advised to narrow my request further. The county suggested I remove e-mail attachments from my request because the downloads were time-consuming and again made my request cumbersome. I consented to removing the attachments for now. More delays.

I was advised to limit my request to a shorter time frame and maybe limit the search terms.  I submitted a new request asking only for e-mails ending in .gov or .org (to cover city/state/fed officials) and adjusted the time frame to just Jan. More delays ensued from @CountyofLA.

Finally I spoke with someone from @CountyofLA who indicated my request was too cumbersome and would result in about 10,000 emails per day. (Which came as a surprise, as my ask was pretty specific -- relating to COVID19 and requesting e-mails from only 2 individuals' email boxes).

In March, I requested e-mails with extremely specific terms related to the coronavirus for a finite period of time (January to early-March) to/from two @lapublichealth leaders. @CountyofLA began a series of delays on the records request. 14 days... another 14 days...

The Lobbyist: At some point between Feb and Mar 2017...Councilmember A conveyed to a "Lobbyist C" that the appeal would be opposed in the city's PLUM Committee. Lobbyist C...agreed to talk it over with the labor coalition. Again...calls to @Creed_LA have not been returned.

According to feds, the developer offered to pay "Councilmember A" $500,000 via Justin Kim to help, after learning it would cost up to $1.4 million to hire a lobbyist to resolve the appeal.  In Feb 2017 court documents say the deal was made. "Councilmember A" would keep $300,000.

According to feds, the bribery scheme began in Sep 2016 when Kim met "Councilmember A", a city staffer and a "Project C" developer at a karaoke bar in LA. Kim asked the councilman to help with the appeal. The councilman said he would not help for free: https://t.co/bJgnBFsnV4

The appeal: 940 South Hill was appealed by a labor coalition called @Creed_LA in Aug 2016, requesting all activity suspended until the development was brought into #CEQA compliance. Appeal was withdrawn in Mar 2017. Calls to Creed LA haven't been returned. https://t.co/SyTBLrIHj2

Who are the developers? 940 South Hill is owned by a company called 940 Hill LLC located at 1020 Crocker St 4th Floor. Business filings I pulled show the officers are Dae Y Lee, Jeong S Kim, and Hyuk S Lim. All calls to the company, its CPA and its officers went unanswered. https://t.co/O7Hs4CuQmP

First let's talk about the Project: 940 South Hill, dubbed "The Hill," was a proposed 420,000 sq ft mixed-use development designed w/ 230+ units, 14,000 sq ft ground-floor retail space & a massive parking garage. This rendering can be found on architecture firm DGB Line's site: https://t.co/yh0r9jKzTf

That would make @josehuizar "Councilmember A," who federal prosecutors allege accepted a $500,000 bribe, facilitated by Kim, in exchange for his assistance with 940 South Hill, which was appealed by a labor organization in Summer 2016.
